@flexiarg t3/participatory-evaluation
@title Participatory Evaluation as Architecture
@sigils [🔬/开]
@audience programme-architects, evaluators, open-research-advocates
@tone formal-analytic
@style design-pattern
@part Open Research Training
@up t3/transformation-space
@see t3/feedback-activation-loop, t3/architectural-pair
@next t3/transformation-space
@length 180-260
@allow-new-claims false

! conclusion:
  The programme teaches open research practices — pre-registration, transparent documentation, peer review — yet its own evaluation infrastructure does not use them. A participatory evaluation design in which training events are treated as open research objects could close the Feedback-Activation Loop through the very practices the programme teaches, simultaneously generating evidence of impact and modelling the behaviour it advocates (Corneli, 2023).

  + context: The Feedback-Activation Loop is the programme's weakest architecture-level pattern; conventional evaluation methods (optional surveys, informal signals) have failed to close it.
  + if: You want to close the feedback gap without adding a separate evaluation burden.
  + however: Participatory evaluation adds complexity and depends on trainer willingness to document and share; institutional compliance requirements may constrain open publication.
  + then: Pilot a participatory evaluation design: trainers pre-register training rationale and expected outcomes, document delivery, and invite structured peer commentary using open infrastructure (e.g., Octopus.ac). Each training event becomes a small, documented experiment that generates impact evidence as a by-product of delivery.
  + because: Embedding evaluation in the training activity itself, using the same open practices the programme promotes, addresses the feedback deficit, models the target behaviour, and generates reusable evidence — three functions for the cost of one.
      + mechanism: Participatory evaluation converts the feedback loop from a separate administrative task into an integral part of the practice, reducing the additional burden and increasing alignment.
      + counterfactual: If evaluation remains external to the training activity, it competes with delivery for scarce time and continues to produce thin, optional data.
      + applies-when: The programme already teaches documentation, pre-registration, and open sharing, and the feedback loop is demonstrably weak.
      + does-not-apply: Programmes with functioning, well-resourced external evaluation; contexts where open documentation of training is prohibited.
      + signals: Feedback surveys produce low response and thin data; trainers cannot demonstrate impact; formal sharing channels go unused.
      + evidence: Present study findings — Feedback-Activation Loop is weakest pattern; COM-B "effects are being measured" M=3.35; cross-institutional sharing channels unused. Corneli (2023) proposed this design prior to the present evaluation; the present findings independently validate the need.
  + next-steps:
      - Pilot with 2-3 willing trainers in the next cohort.
      - Use Octopus.ac or equivalent open platform for documentation.
      - Compare feedback quality and volume with conventional survey methods.
  + governance:
      - practice: review pilot outcomes after one delivery cycle.
      - metric: evidence artefacts produced per training event; trainer assessment of documentation burden.
